'''NTFS''' ('''N'''ew '''T'''echnology '''F'''ile '''S'''ystem) is a proprietary disk [[filesystem]] by Microsoft for Windows and Windows-based operating systems.

== Installation ==

=== Kernel ===

The following kernel options must be enabled for NTFS read/write capabilities in Linux. To get full write support you need to use {{Package|sys-fs/ntfs3g}} package. The kernel implementation offers only limited write support.

{{KernelBox|title=Enabling NTFS using sys-fs/ntfs3g (preferred)|1=
File systems  --->
    <*> FUSE (Filesystem in Userspace) support
}}

{{KernelBox|title=Enabling NTFS with limited write support|1=
File systems  --->
    DOS/FAT/NT Filesystems  --->
        <*> NTFS file system support
        <*>   NTFS write support
}}

=== USE flags ===

{{Package|sys-fs/ntfs3g}} is currently the best implementation of NTFS for Linux:

{{USEflag|package=sys-fs/ntfs3g|desc=Optional USE flags for {{Package|sys-fs/ntfs3g}}:
|acl+yes
|debug++no
|external-fuse+yes
|ntfsdecrypt+++Build and install the ntfsdecrypt application.
|ntfsprogs+yes
|static-libs++no
|suid
|xattr
}}

=== Emerge ===

Install the necessary userspace tools in order to manipulate NTFS filesystems:

{{Emerge|sys-fs/ntfs3g}}

== Usage ==

=== Creation ===

{{Warning|The <tt>mkfs.ntfs</tt> command irreversibly destroys any content of the partition it is told to format. Be sure to select the right partition before running this command!}}

To create an NTFS filesystem on the {{Path|/dev/sda1}} partition (needs <code>ntfsprogs</code> USE flag):
{{RootCmd|mkfs.ntfs /dev/sda1}}

Please replace {{Path|/dev/sda1}} with the actual partition you want to format.

=== Mount ===
There are several ways to mount a NTFS filesystem:
* [[mount]] - Manual mount
* [[fstab]] - Automatic mount at boot time.
* [[removable media]] - Automatic mount at demand.
* [[AutoFS]] - Automatic mount on access.

